</h3><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-brPMkR cnEYUf pf-470_ pf-heading-1-h3">What is basic life support (BLS)?
</h3><p class="sc-iMWBWc laPXAE pf-472_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph3">Basic Life Support (BLS) refers to the level of medical care used for victims of life-threatening illnesses or injuries until they can be given full medical care at a hospital. It includes techniques such as cardiopulmonary resuscitation (CPR) and using an Automated External Defibrillator (AED).
</p><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-brPMkR cnEYUf pf-474_ pf-heading-1-h3">Adult and paediatric basic life support
</h3><p class="sc-iMWBWc laPXAE pf-476_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph3">While based on the same principles, adult BLS and paediatric BLS differ in application due to variations in anatomy and physiology between adults and children. This training ensures that professionals can effectively respond to cardiac emergencies in both adults and children.
